	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EC ‘yellow card’ for Ghana  and South Korea – steps to be taken to avoid blacklisting</h1>

			
			<h4>
												22 December 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>At the end of November, South Korea, Ghana and Curaçao (Netherlands Antilles) were warned by the EC that they should take measures to fight against illegal fishing, or face being put on the EU ‘blacklist’ of non-cooperating countries against IUU fishing.</p><p>Unlike earlier cases (Guinea, Belize, Cambodia), South Korea and Ghana are significant fish trade partners for the EU: Korea exported more than USD$100 million worth of fishery products to the EU in 2012, and Ghana is the third largest tuna-exporting country to the EU.</p><p>The Korean government showed its displeasure with this announcement, saying that the EU warning came despite the revision of the Korean law on long-distance fishing. The law now foresees that all Korean distant-water fishing vessels must be equipped with vessel monitoring systems (VMS), which addresses a key issue raised by the EU. Fines have also been raised: by the end of January, the maximum fine for IUU fishing will be up to three times the value of the IUU catches made. Korean companies – particularly Dongwon, Korea’s largest canned tuna supplier active in African tuna fisheries – are being criticised, because last April, a Dongwon vessel was caught in Liberia fishing without a licence. “The Liberian case garnered attention” an insider is reported to have said. “It is difficult to deny that the company is partly to blame for Korea’s preliminary notification by the EU.”</p><p>In Ghana as well, the EU pre-notification provokes concerns and reactions. The CEO of TradeGAP Africa – a local non-governmental organisation (NGO) that promotes policy dialogue and research in investment and trade issues in Africa – considers that the EU’s threat should be taken seriously. He comments that although quantitative restrictions on imports are deemed inconsistent with general WTO rules, the EU could justify its actions on environmental grounds. Second, “should Ghana like to challenge this measure through the WTO’s dispute settlement system, its fishing industry would likely collapse by the time the WTO panel hears and rules on the case.” The only option for Ghana is to “concentrate its efforts on preventive measures to maintain its export market share for fish products to the EU.”</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Business Korea</i>, Korea displeased being designated illegal fishing nation, 28 November 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.businesskorea.co.kr/article/2301/eu-deep-sea-fishing-korea-displeased-being-designated-illegal-fishing-nation-even-if" target="_self">http://www.businesskorea.co.kr/article/2301/eu-deep-sea-fishing-korea-di...</a></p><p><i>SpyGhana.com</i>, ‘EU yellow cards Ghana and others for illegally fishing in European waters’, 28&nbsp;November 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.spyghana.com/eu-yellow-cards-ghana-and-others-for-illegally-fishing-in-european-waters/" target="_self">http://www.spyghana.com/eu-yellow-cards-ghana-and-others-for-illegally-f...</a></p><p><i>Atuna.com</i>, ‘Gov’t subsidized IUU fishing by Korean fleet?’, 29 November 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.atuna.com/apps/public/ViewArticle.asp?ID=13707" target="_self">http://www.atuna.com/apps/public/ViewArticle.asp?ID=13707</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>In the case of Korea, the information available seems to show that the measures adopted – review of the legislation, increase of the fines – are similar to those taken by other pre-notified third countries, such as Fiji, which were deemed enough to convince the EC that a country like Fiji was able to fight IUU fishing. In the case of Ghana, very few details are known about the criteria that have been applied by the EC – or how they have been applied – leading to this pre-notification. The consequence of not having such information publicly available may give rise to criticisms in the third countries concerned. In another area – the implementation of the sanitary and phytosanitary (SPS) regulations – reports and recommendations from EU veterinary inspections, as well as replies made by the third country authorities, are made accessible to the public. Taking the same approach for the implementation of the EU IUU regulation would help clarify with EU third countries’ partners that this regulation is applied fairly to all.</p>
		</div>
		
